[1] Cholera - Dominican Republic (Pednernales Province)
Date: Wed 18 Nov 2015
Source: El Neuvo Diario [in Spanish, machine trans. edited]
http://www.elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=453076


The Ministry of Health confirmed today [18 Nov 2015] 3 cholera cases in the province of Pedernales, where it had reported several suspected cases of this disease. Deputy of Collective Health Nelson Rodriguez Monegro said people reported episodes of acute diarrheal disease (ADD) in Pedernales.

So far, only 3 tested positive for cholera, and no deaths have been reported from the disease on the Dominican side following the outbreak of the disease detected in Haiti. Through a statement, the official said that for weeks they have been following up on cases of diarrhea that presented in the slums established by the Haitian authorities on the west bank of the Pedernales River in La Paca communities and Step II Sign. He explained that the provincial Elio Fiallo hospital had 22 suspect cases of cholera, 3 of whom are Dominicans, including an employee of the hospital. The others are Haitian nationals.

Monegro Rodriguez explained that cholera was disproven in 5 patients, while the rest remain under observation to determine whether they have the disease. "Currently, the hospital has only 4 patients admitted with acute diarrhea. It was confirmed that 2 of them do not have cholera, and they will be discharged on Tuesday, 24 Nov 2015," he said. At the same time, he said that the next few hours will determine the condition of the others.

Rodriguez said that in the municipality of Duverge, Independencia Province, a Haitian mother and her daughter showed signs of acute diarrhea and were admitted to the Jose Perez municipal hospital and subsequently referred to the Jaime Mota Hospital of Barahona, where they are being hydrated and will be released in the coming hours.

