******
[2] Cholera - Haiti
Date: Sat 31 Oct 2015
Source: UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs [edited]
http://reliefweb.int/report/haiti/haiti-humanitarian-bulletin-issue-55-october-2015


Number of IDPs in camps 2015: 60 801
Cumulative cholera cases (1 Jan 2015 to 19 Sep 2015): 22 511
Fatality cases (1 Jan 20115 to 19 Sep 2015): 185
Cholera outbreak: 15 communes on red alert

With the heavy rains of October 2015, the health officials have observed a resurgence of cholera cases in several communes, notably in the departments of Artibonite, West, South East, South and North. The Pan American Health Organization (PAHO/WHO) in the situation report from 18-29 Oct 2015 affirms that in these departments, more than 400 alerts were recorded.

The document indicates that about 15 communes are on red alert. The situation is more critical in Cite Soleil (91 cases), Marigot (51 cases), St. Mark (36 cases) and Jacmel (33 cases) communes. Humanitarian officials estimate that untreated water consumption and poor hygiene practices are the causes of transmission of 73 percent of the cases investigated.

The UNICEF-PAHO technical team recalled the partners to improve surveillance because the end of the year is the period in which the number of cholera cases tends to increase both in the departments and in the capital. They encouraged better coordination, more flexibility of intervention, and information sharing between actors doing interventions in WASH (water, sanitation and hygiene) and health sectors.

The Pan American Health Organization/World Health Organization (PAHO/WHO), UNICEF, and health departments have intensified activities of rapid response to alerts. Distribution of chlorinated products and oral serum, community awareness, and decontamination of houses, dormitories and sanitary facilities were held in affected communities.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Haiti continues, despite much overt reporting, to be the top of the haystack for cholera cases, underscoring the continued inability of health organizations to effectively reverse the epidemic. Providing clean, safe water and adequate sanitation can go a long way to help minimize the situation. It is not likely that _V. cholerae_ will soon disappear from the water there. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3804308,25.]
